					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285#post-4577900</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285/scp-4061#post-4577900</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Thu, 02 Apr 2020 10:34:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>stopsi99</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>6276788</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>I liked this, but as some other people in this thread have said, it feels like there are too many narratives. The concept is pretty unique, you don't see a lot of SCPs retaining their anomalous properties after death or destruction, and the idea of the real SCP being the genome itself is interesting. Overall a good concept but it needs some refining and a bit more focus, maybe on the idea of the culture getting out of the foundation's control like what was hinted at in the incident log.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285#post-4355743</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285/scp-4061#post-4355743</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 08 Sep 2019 13:56:40 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>5150wned</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5175695</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Read it all, +1.</p> <p>I liked the anomaly, the use of science to pin it down works well for me. But while I liked it, the anomaly&#8230;. basically op as all hell. If the anomaly is the gene sequence itself, spliceable and transferable, anything could have this effect.</p> <p>While your Foundation makes a tool of this anomaly, isn't it easy to see how it could be a bad end? All that has to happen is one mutation of the culture to survive outside the lab and goodbye cameras.</p> <p>Your inclusion of samples getting stolen basically infers this scenario.</p> <p>Basically what I'm saying is do want a tale about K-class scenario where recording is obsolete cause germs.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285#post-4254070</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-8141285/scp-4061#post-4254070</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Sun, 19 May 2019 07:37:27 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Monteparnas</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2926286</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Mostly it is a no-vote, pending to downvote.</p> <p>It isn't bad, per se, but it isn't really interesting, and as DarkStuff points out you have more than one narrative, and neither actually contributes to the other.</p> <p>The set of tests with the dog is redundant, since the gene was already isolated and tested under more controllable environment elsewhere. Also, its toll on the organisms lifespan is for pure shock value without really adding nothing to the story. It doesn't even sell them as too cold, because they didn't had to know the mutt would have the same reduction on lifespan as the bacteria.</p> <p>My suggestion is that you decide what aspect of the article you want to focus on, and develop from there. The story about scientific discovery and manipulation of an anomalous gene? The story of how the anomalous effect affected the short but eventful life of this dog? The espionage drama around the new development that was stolen through a mole inside the Foundation?</p> <p>All of those are interesting concepts for a story, but they all came and went too suddenly here and with no lasting effect on the reader.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
